FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - S. KOREA: OIE
************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 27 May 2002
From: Chris Griot <Christian.Griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE) flash news, 27 May 2002
[edited]

Follow up report on foot and mouth disease (FMD) in the Republic of Korea
------------------------------------------------
Summary of information received on 24 May 2002 from Dr Hee-Woo Lee,
director, Animal Health Division, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry
(MAF), Seoul:

New outbreaks have been reported in 10 farms in Kyonggi-do province and 2
farms in Chungbuk-do province.

Total number of animals in the new outbreaks: 51 233 pigs (first reported
cases included), 116 bovines and 9 deer.
Total number of cases: 613 pigs.
Total number of deaths: 297 pigs.
Total number of animals destroyed: all animals in the 12 affected farms
were destroyed: 51 233 pigs, 116 bovines, and 9 deer.

Epidemiology: FMD outbreaks have been limited to a restricted area. All the
affected farms are located within a 9 km radius around the primary affected
farms.

Control measures during reporting period:
- movement control has been effectively maintained.
- stamping-out policy.
- pre-emptive slaughter has been employed to contain the spread of FMD
within the controlled areas.

Further details will be published in the next issue of Weekly Disease
Information, available online as from Friday 31 May 2002 afternoon (GMT).

